 0002: Module of cythonized functions for basic computational geometry in 2
 0003: and 3 dimensions. This modules requires geometric objects (e.g.
 0004: polygons, polyhedra, surfaces, segments, etc.) to be described as a
 0005: collection of simplices (i.e. segments or triangles). In this module,
 0006: geometric objects in D-dimensional space are described with an (N, D)
 0007: array of vertices and and (M, D) array describing the indices of
 0008: vertices making up each simplex. As an example, the unit square in two
 0009: dimensions can be described as collection of line segments:
 0010: 
 0011: >>> vertices = [[0.0, 0.0],
 0012:                 [1.0, 0.0],
 0013:                 [1.0, 1.0],
 0014:                 [0.0, 1.0]]
 0015: >>> simplices = [[0, 1],
 0016:                  [1, 2],
 0017:                  [2, 3],
 0018:                  [3, 0]]
 0019: 
 0020: A three dimensional cube can similarly be described as a collection
 0021: of triangles:
 0022: 
 0023: >>> vertices = [[0.0, 0.0, 0.0],
 0024:                 [0.0, 0.0, 1.0],
 0025:                 [0.0, 1.0, 0.0],
 0026:                 [0.0, 1.0, 1.0],
 0027:                 [1.0, 0.0, 0.0],
 0028:                 [1.0, 0.0, 1.0],
 0029:                 [1.0, 1.0, 0.0],
 0030:                 [1.0, 1.0, 1.0]]
 0031: >>> simplices = [[0, 1, 4],
 0032:                  [1, 5, 4],
 0033:                  [1, 7, 5],
 0034:                  [1, 3, 7],
 0035:                  [0, 1, 3],
 0036:                  [0, 2, 3],
 0037:                  [0, 2, 6],
 0038:                  [0, 4, 6],
 0039:                  [4, 5, 7],
 0040:                  [4, 6, 7],
 0041:                  [2, 3, 7],
 0042:                  [2, 6, 7]]
 0043:  
 0044: This module is primarily used to find whether and where line segments
 0045: intersect a geometric object and whether points are contained within a
 0046: closed geometric object.  For example, one can determine whether a
 0047: collection of points, saved as `points`, are contained within a
 0048: geometric object, defined by `vertices` and `simplices` with the
 0049: command
 0050: 
 0051: >>> contains(points, vertices, simplices)
 0052: 
 0053: which returns a boolean array.
 0054: 
 0055: One can find the number of times a collection of line segments,
 0056: defined by `start_points` and `end_points`, intersect a geometric
 0057: object with the command
 0058: 
 0059: >> intersection_count(start_points, end_points, vertices, simplices)
 0060: 
 0061: which returns an array of the number of simplices intersected by each
 0062: segment. If it is known that a collection of line segments intersect a
 0063: geometric object then the intersection point can be found with the
 0064: command
 0065: 
 0066: >> intersection(start_points, end_points, vertices, simplices)
 0067:  
 0068: This returns an (N, D) float array of intersection points, and an (N,)
 0069: int array identifying which simplex the intersection occurred at. If a
 0070: line segment does not intersect the geometric object then the above
 0071: command returns a ValueError. If there are multiple intersections for
 0072: a single segment then only the first detected intersection will be
 0073: returned.
 0074: 
 0075: There are numerous other packages which can perform the same tasks as
 0076: this module.  For example geos (http://trac.osgeo.org/geos/) and gts
 0077: (http://gts.sourceforge.net/).  However, the python bindings for these
 0078: packages are too slow for RBF purposes.

The line segments are described by `start_points` and\n  `end_points`, and the simplicial complex is described by `vertices`\n  and `simplices`. This function works for 2 and 3 spatial dimensions.\n\n  Parameters\n  ----------\n  start_points : (N, D) float array\n    Vertices describing one end of the line segments. `N` is the\n    number of line segments and `D` is the number of dimensions\n\n  end_points : (N, D) float array \n    Vertices describing the other end of the line segments. \n\n  vertices : (M, D) float array \n    Vertices within the simplicial complex. M is the number of \n    vertices.\n\n  simplices : (P, D) int array\n    Connectivity of the vertices. Each row contains the vertex \n    indices which form one simplex of the simplicial complex\n\n  Returns\n  -------\n  out : (N, D) float array\n    The points where the line segments intersect the simplicial\n    complex\n\n  out : (N,) int array\n    The index of the simplex that the line segments intersect\n\n  Notes\n  -----\n  This function fails when a intersection is not found for a line\n  segment. If there are multiple intersections then the intersection\n  closest to start_point is used.\n\n  ";

 0984:   ''' 
 0985:   Returns the intersection between line segments and a simplicial
 0986:   complex.  The line segments are described by `start_points` and
 0987:   `end_points`, and the simplicial complex is described by `vertices`
 0988:   and `simplices`. This function works for 2 and 3 spatial dimensions.
 0989: 
 0990:   Parameters
 0991:   ----------
 0992:   start_points : (N, D) float array
 0993:     Vertices describing one end of the line segments. `N` is the
 0994:     number of line segments and `D` is the number of dimensions
 0995: 
 0996:   end_points : (N, D) float array 
 0997:     Vertices describing the other end of the line segments. 
 0998: 
 0999:   vertices : (M, D) float array 
 1000:     Vertices within the simplicial complex. M is the number of 
 1001:     vertices.
 1002: 
 1003:   simplices : (P, D) int array
 1004:     Connectivity of the vertices. Each row contains the vertex 
 1005:     indices which form one simplex of the simplicial complex
 1006: 
 1007:   Returns
 1008:   -------
 1009:   out : (N, D) float array
 1010:     The points where the line segments intersect the simplicial
 1011:     complex
 1012: 
 1013:   out : (N,) int array
 1014:     The index of the simplex that the line segments intersect
 1015: 
 1016:   Notes
 1017:   -----
 1018:   This function fails when a intersection is not found for a line
 1019:   segment. If there are multiple intersections then the intersection
 1020:   closest to start_point is used.

Each row contains the vertex \n    indices which form one simplex of the simplicial complex\n\n  use_qotree : bool, optional\n    Use a quad-tree or oct-tree to reduce the number of simplices\n    queried for each segment. Building and querying the tree does\n    introduce overhead.  1057:   Returns the number of simplices crossed by the line segments. The

 1066: 
 1067:   end_points : (N, D) array 
 1068:     Vertices describing the other end of the line segments
 1069: 
 1070:   vertices : (M, D) array

 1073:
